{"/service/ndnp/txdn/batch_txdn_evans_ver01/data/sn86063730/00332894195/1930022102/0391.xml":{"full_text":"jr Snramsuffle HeraW\nEstablished July 4, 1892\nEntered u xcond-clwa matter uTtha Rtofflcs-\u2019\nBrownsville, Texas.\nTHE BROWNSVILLE HERALD PCBl^BlNG\nCOMPANY\nSubscription Rates\u2014Dally and Sunday n u^nT 1\nYaar _*900 j\nBlx Months $450\nThree Months.....1225 1\nOne Month.... 75 1\nMEMBER OF THE ASSOCIATED PlU>>\nThe Associated Press Is exclusively entitled to tbe use\nfor publication of all news dispatches credited to it or!1\nnot otherwise credited In this paper, and also the\nlocal news published herein.\nHarlingen Office, Reese-Wil-Mond Hotel, Phone 1020.\n1\nTEXAS DAILY PRESS LEAGUE\nNational Advertising Representatives\nDallas. Texas, 512 Mercantile Bank Building.\nKansas City. Mo., 306 Coca Cola Building.\nChicago. Ill, Association Building. 1\nNew York, 350 Madison Avenue.\nSt. Louis. 502 Star Building.\nLos Angeles. Cal, Room 1015 New Orpheum Bldg..\nB46 S. Broadway.\nSan Francisco, Cal., 318 Kohl Building.\nMexico and Our Water Supply\nGood relations with Mexico are of extreme Import\nance to the Valley just now.\nThe immediate reason is that a water treaty guar\nanteeing the Valley's supply is being negotiated.\nThe general reason Is. of course, that we want to\nlive on friendly relations with our neighbors.\nWhen the Valley is faced with this situation, con\ngressmen from our own state are doing everything\nthey can to pass legislation which will hurt us.\nAbout 60 per cent of the water which comes dowr.\nthe Rio Grande in the Valley comes from streams in\nMexico. Mexico could take all this water before it\nreaches the Rio Grande, and nothing could be said\nShe is now building dams to carry out part of tha?\nj possibility.\niThls might hurt the Valley under present condi\ntions.\nStill there Is no reason for alarm on the water\nsituation, if friendly* relations can be kept with Mexi\nco. so that storage dams can be built.\nWe are told by engineers that the annual flow\nof the Rio Grande is around 5,000.000 acre-feet. Less\nthan 1.000.000 acre-feet is now used in irrigation\nalong the river, and much of this is wasted in faulty\nIrrigation works.\nThere is plenty of water for all. if storage dams\nare built to conserve the water.\nNegotiations have been in progress for some tim'1\nto reach a water treaty with Mexico bo that such\ndams can be built.\nEverything that tends to disrupt friendly rela\ntions with Mexico hurts our chance for such a treaty.\nThe Box bill, the Johnson bill, Mexicans illeeally\ndeported\u2014all such unwise and unfriendly actions\nwill hurt the Valley in its chance to secure its water\nguarantees.\nWe claim the normal flow of the Rio Grande as\nours by right of prior beneficial use. If our govern\ni ment follows a reasonable course. It seems certain\nthese rights will be guaranteed to us.\nBut we should remember, and should impress the\nfact on our congressmen from North Texas, that\nMexico has the power to take the water, since It\noriginates in her country*, and that she is fast pre\nparing to do so.\nDisarming the Mexican Pistol\nToters\nPresident Pascual Rubio of Mexico has launched\na campaign against the automatic. That is he has\nfnstructed the police authorities of the City of Mexico\nto confiscate the pistols of all persons who are without\npermit. It is a very drastic order. Rubio plans to\ntake pistols away from the entire civilian popula\ntion of the republic. After he has recovered suf\nficiently to direct the work personally he intends to\nwithdraw all pistol permits. It Is another noble ex\nperiment. Rubio Is an engineer. There is an engi\nI neer president of the United States. He is wrestling\nwith a noble experiment and all its perplexing ln\ntracacies.\nThe Once Over\nBy H. L PHILLIPS\nL' 1\nMORE NEWS FROM THE WINTER RESORTS\n(Copyright, 1930, by The Associated Newspapers.)\nBt. Augustine, Fla.\u2014Mr. and Mrs. Winfield Zilch\nlave arrived here by automobile from their home in\nDayton, Ohio. The unhappy couple make the trip\nly car every season if It kills them. This year Mr.\nSilch looked particularly weakened by back-seat driv\nng. \u2018TU be all right again by the time we\u2019re ready\no start back,\u201d he sighed wearily from his hotel bed\noday.\nMr. and Mrs. Gregory Dilldoch and their police\nlog Napoleon also tooled into town by auto this\nnorning, looking much the worse for wear after a\n[,400-mile drive from 8pringfield, Mass. The dog\nitood it as long as it could but turned on Mr. Dill\nloci: and bit him passing through Brunswick, Geor\ngia. Mr. Dilldoch stood it as far as Jacksonville\nvhere he bit both the dog and Mrs. Dilldoch.\nColonel and Mrs. Jeptha Willetts, who come here\near after year without having much of an idea how\no enjoy themselves, are spending their usual two\nveeks arguing with hackmen and storekeepers over\n\u2022ates.\nThe croquet players are at it in the public square\nind the enmities incurred have exceeded the 1929 fig\nires by 20 per cent, so far, with the season still\nI'OUXlg.\nThe guides outside the old Spanish fort on the\nsvaterfront are pretty disgusted. Two Northern\nschoolgirls walked up to them this week and asked\nif it was off here that the Maine was sunk.\nORMOND\nGathering at the first tee every morning at 10\na\u2019clock to see the wrorld\u2019s most famous golfer drive off\nis still the chief outdoor sport here. No, not Bobby\nTones; John D. Rockefeller.\nMr. Rockefeller plays eight holes a day. He Is 90\nyears old and that is also his average score.\nMr and Mrs. Wesley Prunedlsh, who are spending\na few days here, will wait one day more. If the oil\nicinar doesn't give them a new dime they will de\nnounce him and leave.\nMotoring up and down the beach between here\nar.d Daytona Beach continues to be the favorite\nrecreation of thousands of visitors whose ideas of\ndiversion are hard to understand.\nDAYTONA BEACH\nMr end Mrs. Emory D. L. Whlpsay are both con\nfined to their beds under the care of doctors. They\nanswered one of those newspaper advertisements\nreading. \"Lady and gentleman motoring South in\nlive-passenger car can accommodate another con\ngenial couple.\u201d The gentleman turned out to be an\nunreformed dirt-track automobile racer. The lady,\naccording to Mrs. Whipsaw, was no lady.\nMr. and Mrs. Casper Mulligitawney of Penobscot.\nMaine, who came here by flivver, are very indignant\nbecause, although there are three or four free\nbridges across the Halifax river they had to choose\nthe one toll-bridge.\nMr and Mrs. Luke Cupcake and their daughter,\nAbbie, who arrived here with a new camera Thursday.\nhav\u00bb used up their tenth film taking pictures of one\nanother In front of the swell hotels, although they are\nputting up at a boarding-house.\nMajor T. Haithwalte Palooka, who came here by\nauto, is waxing quite Indignant because he was held\nup by police put on the roads In the Florida fruit\nfly quarantine. \"Do I look like a fruit-fly?\u201d he\ndemands. People are slow In answering him.\nCan you fancy the broodlngs in after life of a girl\nchosen Miss Universe and who later loses her looks\nRnri becomes just plain Mrs. Addison Gimlet or some\nthin? like that?\nThe rediscount rate has dropped to 4 per cent, and\nTma Dodo says she doesn\u2019t care as she sold hers at\n414.\nI THE OLD HOME TOWN Stanley\nW 1\nIII';\nN\nj OTtY, A FEU.ER\nJUST phone-din FROM\nSTAGNATION CENTE|9#\nHE SAID a STRANGER\nWENT SAIL IN \"OVER\nTh' town 'Bout 700\nEVERY THING FEET UP IN A BIG\nwent black'! cloud of o' dust-\nGUESS THAT WAS\nI tour, prisoner.\n11 i i. .\u25a0\u25a0ii i \u2014i s\nNEWS NOTE- THE LOCAL. JAIL WAS PRACTICALLY\nBLOWN OUT OP THE COUNTS TODAY/ WHEN A\n)i Bottle op so called \"good stuff\"exploded-|\nTHE BOOTLBCSBR prisoner WAS HEAt>JM$ DUE. -_\u2014.._\nWEST WHEN LAST SEEN HE V/AS TRAV^lW^ ATA WSHPAT OFSPEEp\nL <a\u00bb9>c Lgc w ctnT\u00bb>L rncs* g-ZI\u00bb3e>\nCHAPTER 50\nIt was, perhaps, fifteen minutes\nlater that Captain Lee entered the\ncabin and took his seat at the din\ning table. The deck hand had of\nfered no resistance whatever, he\nsaid, not even asking the reason\nfor locking him up.\n\u201cHe knows the reason well\nenough!\u201d declared Margery, her\nblue eyes flashing at the recollec\ntion of the fellows deed. \"He knew\nI had recognized him when he saw\nme. That\u2019s why he turned and ran!\nHe has been very careful since we\nleft New York to keep out of my\nSight. It was Just by a lucky chance\n\u2014for us\u2014that I saw him tonight!\"\nThe incident was the sole topic,\nalmost, throughout the dinner. Ev\nery conceivable conjecture was ad\nvanced as to what form of deviltry\nexecution of the fellow\u2019s plan would\nhave taken. That Jimmy was to\nhave been the victim none doubted.\nIt was the general belief, also, that\nthe purno^p had been murder.\nAs Pat and her guests were about\nto r. ie ircm the table. Captain Lee\nturned to the yacht's new owner,\na look of concern on his weather\nbeaten face.\n\u201cIt would be the part of wisdom,\nMiss Blair,\u201d he said in his slow7,\ncareful way of speaking, \"so long\nas you aren t in any particular hur\nry7. for us to drop anchor somewhere\nalong here and wait for davlight\nbefore we proceed. As I\u2019ve told vou,\nthere are many hidden coral reefs\nin these waters and we might slam\nonto one, even though there is a\nfull moon. What do you think about\nit? Shall we keep on running oi\ndrop the hook?\n\"Oh. if there is any danger, Cap\ntain. I'd say to anchor, by all\nmeans!\" replied Pat. She looked in\nquiringly at the others. Don't you\nall agree?\" she queried.\nThe question received a general\naffirmative answer. Ten minutes\nlater the Bluebird came to a stop\nsome two miles off the east shore\nof Barbados, where anchorage was\nfound.\nThe warm, perfumed air of the\ntropical night drew everyone to the\nvessel\u2019s after deck to which easy\nchairs had been brought up by the\nwaiters from the cabin. The big\nsouthern moon, double in size,\nseemingly, to the moon of the\nnorth, was Just riding out of the\nocean in the east.\n\"Glorious, wonderful!\" breathed\nPat. a little quiver of rapture in the\nsweet contralto tones as she lav\nback In her chair, her eyes uplifted\nand shining in the sky's reflected\nsplendor. Two men sitting close by\nand facing her, one on each side,\nj Grab Bag\nFebruary 21. 1930\nWho am I? What state do I rep\nresent in the senate? Whom did I\nsucceed?\nWho Is the president general of\nthe Daughters of the American\nRevolution?\nWhat Is the capital of Jamaica?\n\u201cAnd whosoever shall offend one\nof these little ones that believe In\nme, it is better for him that a mill\nstone were hanged about his neck,\nand he were cast into the sea.\"\nWhere is this passage found in the\nBible?\nCorrectly Speaking\u2014\nRemember, constant usage of an\nexpression does not make it good\nEnglish. Think of this the next time\nyou say \"hadn\u2019t ought\" or \"he dont.\u201d\nToday's Anniversary\nOn this date, in 1885, the Wash\nington monument was dedicated in\nthe District of Columbia.\nToday\u2019s Horoscope\nPersons born on this day are very\nreliable. They can be trusted to\nwork without supervision.\nAnswcxs to Foregoing Questions\n1. Roscoe C. McCulloch; Ohio;\nTheodore E. Burton.\n2. Mrs. Lowell F. Hobart.\n3. Kingston.\n4. St. Mark, ix. 42. _\nStar Lore\nTHE BIRTH OF A STAR\nBy Arthur DeV. Carpenter\nIt would be wonderful to be able\nto trace the actual beginning of a\nstar. The astronomer and scientist\ncan quite effectively go back in his\nintelligent imagination and behold\nthe time when there was a very thin\ngas distributed through space. This\ninfinitely vast cloud doubtless broke\nup and formed galaxies of spiral\nnebulae, and finally each spiral\nnebulae condensed into stars. At\nfirst a star must have been of so\nthin a composition that to be com\npared with anything material of\nwhich we know, it would be the\nequivalent of a near vacuum. Then\nby process covering untold ages, it\ncondensed, and generated heat and\nI light.\nlooked Into the dark eyes, humid\nin the light of the moon and they,\ntoo, murmured: \u201cGlorious, wonder\nful!\u201d But neither referred to the\nglory or the wonder of the sky.\nJimmy Blair occupied a deep\ncushioned chair nearby. In close\nproximity, so close she had but to\nmove her hand a few inches to rest\nit on his, sat Margery. Jimmy also\nlay with his head back gazing up\ninto the brilliantly lit heavens.\nLooking into his eyes the girl mar\nvelled at the inexplicable mystery\nthat lay behind them. Of what was\nhe thinking? For It was Inconceiv\nable that no thought of any de\nscription occupied that twisted\nbrain. He must be thinking of\nsomething. What was it?\nHad she possessed the power to\nproject the off-put of her own mind\ninto the midst of coming events\nand read there the underlying story\nthat destiny was then shaping, she\nwould have marvelled even more\nover the strange workings cf the\nhuman brain. Not possessing that\npower she confined her attention\nto matters at hand.\nThen someone suggested a song,\nwhereupon, Lucy\u2019s guitar was\nbrought up and the latest popular\nairs began to waft their melody\nacross the calm waters of the Car\nibbean. Rex had a good tenor voice\nand the doctor owned an uncom\nmonly good bass. These with Pat's\nrich contralto, and the sopranos of\nthe two other girls, produced a com\nbination equal to many of the\nprofessional quintettes.\nit, was eleven ocjock ana alter\nbefore the deck party began to dis\nintegrate. First, the lawyer and his\nwife and Aunt Lottie retired to\ntheir staterooms. Then Dr. Gordon\nrose, stretched luxuriously apd de\nclared himself \u201cabout ready to hit\nthe hay.\u201d But he must have chang\ned his mind almost immediately,\nfor instead of retiring to the cabin,\nhe strolled forward. A few minutes\nafterward Lucy and Margery, tak\ning Jimmy with them, started for\nthe galley with the avowed Inten\ntion of \u201ccopping a snack Pat and\nRex were thus left to the seclusion\nof their own devices.\n\u201cDon't you feel the spell of this\nwonderful night, Rex?\" asked the\ngirl, breaking a long silence that\nfollowed the departure of Jimmy\nand his escorts. \u201cI just love to sit\nhere and watch the stars glimmer\nand glow! And that marvelous\nmoon! Isn't It all Just perfectly\ngrand?\"\n1 As she put the query her gaze\nshifted from the heavenly bodies,\ndropping to the level of the man's\neyes in which lay revealed, all the\nunspoken love in his heart. In the\ndark eyes looking straight Into his\nhe read something\u2014or thought he\ndid. at least\u2014that he had not dared\nhone ever to see there. A little cry\ngurgled from his lips and he caught\nher hand, lying in her lap, in both\nof his.\n\u2022\u2022Pat\u2014my dear!\u201d The name and\nthe endearing term were not spoken.\nThey were gasped out with a trem\nbling huskiness. \u201c1\u20141\u2014\u201d Some\nthing rose tip in his throat. He\nswallowed it with a mighty effort,\nand tried again. \u201cYou know. dear,\nthat I\u2014I love you!\u201d Again he was\nforced to stop. It was the hardest\nwork that had ever been put upon\nRex Pa\u2019lard in his entire life.\nOnce more he swallowed the lump.\nThen: \u201cI can't ex\u2014expect, of course,\nthat\u2014that you care for me! That\nis as I care, but I do love you. Pat.\nvery dearly!\"\n\u201cDo you, Rex\u2014dear?\u201d came the\nsoftlv whispered acknowledgement.\nWhether it was meant for a con\nfession of love on her part or not.\nit must have sounded so to Rex\u2014\nand strangely sweet, too\u2014if the\nswiftness of motion with which he\nleaned over, caught her two arms\nand pulled her forward on his lap\nin the inclosure of the deep chair\nwas any evidence. And from the\nmanner in which she accented and\n\u2014ves, returned\u2014his ardent kiss it\nmust have been a correct assump\ntion on Rex's part that he hadn't\nmade any grievous mistake. To\nmake doubly certain he becan an\nother. _\nIt was this one that Dr. Gordon,\nhaving smoked an entire cigar In\nthe solitude of the yacht's port\nbow, where he had stood commun\ning with the spirit of the night,\nhappened to glimpse as he stepped\ninto the opening of the after-deck.\nThat the sight was a Jolt to the\ndoctor's pey e of mind, there ran be\nbut little doubt. Judging by his ac\ntions. For, as his gaze settled on\nthe couple In the big chair, the\nlight from the moon clearly out\nlining the two. the man's face bent\ndown over the girl\u2019s upturned to\nhis. Dr. Gordon stopped short. For\nft second or two he stood there and\nthen turning, lurched rather than\nwalked, hack to the place in the\nI port bow. where he had stood\ndreaming a dream\u2014a futile, lmpos\nsible dream, he now realized.\nAnd the two back on the after\ndeTk sitting in the mellow light of\nthe Southern moon -thev were\nj living through the first fond rap\ni tures of their love\u2019s dream. And\nas thev sat there under the stars\ni he told her again the old story....\nand she listened and smiled Just as\nSAMBO\u2019S PHILOSOPHY\n\u201cFeme folkses uevah think\u00ae 'bout\nsavin\u2019 up fo\u2019 a rainy day \u2019til hit g.ia\nblack, an\u2019 begins to tkundah.\u201d\nO SAY\u2014\no SAY C'AN you SEE. By 1\n-ifiE DAWN'S EARLY UOHT; S\nV/MAT DA CE DE- DA DA DA DA\u2014\nk DA DE DA da DA DE. DA DA\nWE. WA*TtlWEO DA DADE\n:s _/\nwomen have listened and smiled!\ndown through the centuries.\nIt was one of the waiters coming\nup to carry the chairs back into the\ncabin that brought the couple out\nof their dream and sent Pat scur\nrying down to her stateroom. Rex\nfollowed shortly afterward to his\nown.\nRex and Jimmy occupied the last\napartment on the starboard side,\nadjoining the entrance into the\nlazarette. Jimmy had the lower and\nRex the upper berth.\nAfter reaching the seclusion of\nher stateroom, Pat stood for a few\nmoments looking out the window\non the moon-lit ocean.\n(TO BE CONTINUED)\nRio Hondo Climbing\nAs Shipping Center\n(Special to The Herald.)\nRIO HONDO, Feb. 21\u2014Setting a\nnew record for daily average ship\nment of citrus and other agricul\ntural products of better than four\ncarloads, and reaching a new high\ntotal for the season of 150 carloads\nto date. Rio Hondo has climbed to\nseventh place in the Calley ship\nping.\nFleures to this effect were re\nleased this week by A. B. Waldron,\nex^iutive general agent for the\nMissouri Pacific Railway.\nA year ago this town was In\nfourteenth place In regard to agri\ncultural produce movement. Rapid\ndevelopment and opening up of\nnew land to farming has made this\nnew record possible, it is asserted.\nIncluded in the total of 150 cars\nare 141 vegetables and nine citrus.\nPFFR\u2019S IVU C.HTFR AIR PILOT\nLONDON\u2014The daughter of Lord\nInchcape has passed the air pilot\ntests and bought an aeroplane for\nher personal use._\nWe have added a\nRental Library to our\nstore! Come in and look I\nI it over. All of the best 2\nsellers of all publishers. T\nKeep abreast of the j\nmost popular new books\nby renting them at I\nsmall cost!\nHARGROVE\u2019S 1\nStationery Book Store\nPhone 348\nTake the safe and proved remedy\nlaxative quinine. It\ncleanses the system and the\nquinine relieves the cold.\nGrove\u2019s\ndruggitt*\nLaxative\nBROMO\nQUININE\nTablets*\nI\n1 Day In Congress j\n(By Associated Press.)\nFriday:\nSenate:\nContinues consideration of tariff\nbill.\nLobby committee continues Mus\ncle Shoals investigation.\nHouse:\nContinued consideration of first\ndeficiency bill under the five-min\nute rule.\nBanking committee holds hearing\non bill to provide federal examiners\nfor federal land and joint stock\nland ranks.\nThursday:\nSenate:\nCompleted consideration of agri\ncultural rates in tariff bill.\nConfirmed nomination of Hugh M.\nTate of Knoxville, Tennessee, as\nmember of interstate commerce\ncommission.\nHouse;\nCompleted general debate on first\ndeficiency bill.\nHeard protest by chairman White\nof Merchant Marine committee\nagainst \"unfair\u201d practices of Can\nada and the Cunard line against\nAmerican shipping interests.\nJudiciary committee took addi\ntional testimony on proposals to re\npeal or amend eighteenth amend\nment.\nCHILD FINDS FAMILY DEAD\nDULUTH, Minn\u2014Returning from\na party, 8-year-old Florence Kilgore\nfound her parents and two bro\nthers asphyxiated.\nA. TAMM\nBlue Printing and\nSupplies\nHarlingen, Texas\n1911 1930\nSkelton Abstract Co.\nAbstracts of Title Title Insurance\nMerchants Bank Building Brownsville\n1\nPR SPERITY\nProsperity for Brownsville and\nthe Valley is a tangible, able-to\nbe-seen condition. Citrus groves\nare beginning to bloom vege\ntables are commanding good\nprices generally the interna\ntional airport and the bright\nprospects for a deep water port\u2014\nall are encouraging a splendid\nbusiness outlook for Brownsville\nand the Valley.\nLet us, as your bank, help\nyou with any problems you\nmay wish to discuss with us.\nFirst National Bank\nEstablished in 1891\nBROWNSVILLE, TEXAS\n1\nm\nI TITLE INSURANCE j\nWhen you borrow money on real estate, many loan companies re\nquire the title to be insured. I he best test of w hether a title ts\ninsurable, is to have it insured. Require a title insurance policy\nwhen you buy.\nVALLEY ABSTRACT COMPANY.\nPrompt Title Service\nBrownsville\nOpposite Court House\nPhone 1184 4\nEdinburg\nE. Ilarriman Bird.\nPhone 93","height":"36400","width":"27656"}}
